# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: knot-unit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] In physics, **acceleration** is a measure of how fast and in what direction an object's speed and direction of motion are changing.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] It is defined as the rate of change of the velocity.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] Like velocity, acceleration has a magnitude and a direction, making it a vector quantity.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] The SI unit for acceleration is metre per second squared (m⋅s−2, m/s2).
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] The **tangential acceleration** of an object is the component of the **acceleration** which is in the same direction as the motion (or tangential velocity) of the object.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] When the velocity of the object does not change direction, this is called **linear acceleration**.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] **Deceleration** or **retardation**, on the other hand, is the component of the acceleration in the opposite (or antiparallel) direction to the tangential velocity.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] **Radial acceleration** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motions) is the component of the acceleration that changes the direction of the object's velocity.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] In Newtonian mechanics, the acceleration of a mass arises from forces acting on it, with its *net* acceleration being a result of the *net* force acting on it.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] By Newton's second law, the magnitude of the *net* acceleration will be proportional to the magnitude of the *net* force acting on the object and inversely proportional to the mass of the object, while the direction of the *net* acceleration will be the same as the direction of the *net* force.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] An object's average acceleration ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}$ over a period of time is its change in velocity, $\Delta \mathbf {v}$ , divided by the duration of the period, $\Delta t$ .
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] Mathematically, ${\bar {\mathbf {a} }}={\frac {\Delta \mathbf {v} }{\Delta t}}.$ The average acceleration is the simplest way to measure acceleration, requiring only knowledge of the change in velocity and the change in time.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] In a strict sense, the average acceleration is the only *true* acceleration one is able to directly measure without appealing to an empirical law, meaning that it is the most fundamental form of acceleration measurement.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] The average acceleration is most often used to approximate the kinematics of an object by assuming that the velocity changes linearly with time.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] Instantaneous acceleration is the limit of the average acceleration over an infinitesimal interval of time.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] Acceleration has the dimensions of velocity (L/T) divided by time, i.e.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] The SI unit of acceleration is the metre per second squared (m s−2); or "metre per second per second", as the velocity in metres per second changes by the acceleration value, every second.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] An object moving in a circular motion—such as a satellite orbiting the Earth—is accelerating due to the change of direction of motion, although its speed may be constant.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] In this case it is said to be undergoing *centripetal* (directed towards the center) acceleration.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] Proper acceleration, the acceleration of a body relative to a free-fall condition, is measured by an instrument called an accelerometer.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] Newton's second law is normally applied in an inertial reference frame.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] In a reference frame accelerating with acceleration a (in one dimension), Newton's laws can still be used by introducing an inertial force (fictitious force) $F=-ma$ on a mass m , opposite the acceleration of the frame.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] This accounts for the tendency of the mass to maintain its inertial motion—to stay "as is," at rest or moving at constant velocity—while the frame accelerates.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] One example is that a person in an elevator feels heavier or lighter as the elevator accelerates or decelerates.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] If m is known, measurement of the supporting force on the mass can be used to infer the acceleration; this is the principle of a mechanical accelerometer.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] In general relativity, gravity and inertial acceleration may be locally indistinguishable (see General relativity).
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] As speeds approach the speed of light, relativistic effects become increasingly large.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] When a vehicle starts from a standstill (zero velocity, in an inertial frame of reference) and travels in a straight line at increasing speeds, it is accelerating in the direction of travel.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] If the vehicle turns, an acceleration occurs toward the new direction and changes its motion vector.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] The component of acceleration of the vehicle in the direction of its velocity is called a **linear acceleration** or **tangential acceleration**, its effect being the passengers on board experience as a fictitious force pushing them back into or away from their seats.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] When changing direction, the component of the acceleration perpendicular to the velocity is called **radial** or **normal acceleration** (or **centripetal acceleration** during circular motion), the reaction to which the passengers experience as a centrifugal force (another fictitious force).
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] If the speed of the vehicle decreases, this is an acceleration in the opposite direction of the velocity vector, sometimes called **deceleration** or **retardation**, and passengers experience the reaction to deceleration as an inertial force pushing them forward.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] Such deceleration is often achieved by retrorocket burning in spacecraft.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] Both acceleration and deceleration are treated the same, as they are both changes in velocity.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] Each of these accelerations (tangential, radial, deceleration) is felt by passengers until their relative (differential) velocity is neutralised in reference to the acceleration due to change in speed.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] where **u**n is the unit (inward) normal vector to the particle's trajectory (also called *the principal normal*), and **r** is its instantaneous radius of curvature based upon the osculating circle at time t.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] Geometrical analysis of three-dimensional space curves, which explains tangent, (principal) normal and binormal, is described by the Frenet–Serret formulas.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] A frequently cited example of uniform acceleration is that of an object in free fall in a uniform gravitational field.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] The acceleration of a falling body in the absence of resistances to motion is dependent only on the gravitational field strength g (also called *acceleration due to gravity*).
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] In particular, the motion can be resolved into two orthogonal parts, one of constant velocity and the other according to the above equations.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] As Galileo showed, the net result is parabolic motion, which describes, e.g., the trajectory of a projectile in vacuum near the surface of Earth.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] , always points radially from the origin.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] , not parallel to the radial motion but offset by the angular and Coriolis accelerations, nor tangent to the path but offset by the centripetal and radial accelerations.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] plane in a point of an arbitrary curve in any higher dimension.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] In uniform circular motion, that is moving with constant *speed* along a circular path, a particle experiences an acceleration resulting from the change of the direction of the velocity vector, while its magnitude remains constant.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] The derivative of the location of a point on a curve with respect to time, i.e. its velocity, turns out to be always exactly tangential to the curve, respectively orthogonal to the radius in this point.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] Since in uniform motion the velocity in the tangential direction does not change, the acceleration must be in radial direction, pointing to the center of the circle.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] This acceleration constantly changes the direction of the velocity to be tangent in the neighbouring point, thereby rotating the velocity vector along the circle.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] This acceleration and the mass of the particle determine the necessary centripetal force, directed *toward* the centre of the circle, as the net force acting on this particle to keep it in this uniform circular motion.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] The so-called 'centrifugal force', appearing to act outward on the body, is a so-called pseudo force experienced in the frame of reference of the body in circular motion, due to the body's linear momentum, a vector tangent to the circle of motion.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] The tangential component is given by the angular acceleration $\alpha$ , i.e., the rate of change $\alpha ={\dot {\omega }}$ of the angular speed $\omega$ times the radius r .
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] The sign of the tangential component of the acceleration is determined by the sign of the angular acceleration ( $\alpha$ ), and the tangent is always directed at right angles to the radius vector.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] In multi-dimensional Cartesian coordinate systems, acceleration is broken up into components that correspond with each dimensional axis of the coordinate system.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] The special theory of relativity describes the behaviour of objects travelling relative to other objects at speeds approaching that of light in vacuum.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] Newtonian mechanics is exactly revealed to be an approximation to reality, valid to great accuracy at lower speeds.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] As the relevant speeds increase toward the speed of light, acceleration no longer follows classical equations.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] As speeds approach that of light, the acceleration produced by a given force decreases, becoming infinitesimally small as light speed is approached; an object with mass can approach this speed asymptotically, but never reach it.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] Unless the state of motion of an object is known, it is impossible to distinguish whether an observed force is due to gravity or to acceleration—gravity and inertial acceleration have identical effects.
[src:knot-unit/acceleration] Albert Einstein called this the equivalence principle, and said that only observers who feel no force at all—including the force of gravity—are justified in concluding that they are not accelerating.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] An **adiabatic process** (*adiabatic* from Ancient Greek ἀδιάβατος*(*adiábatos*)* 'impassable') is a type of thermodynamic process whereby a transfer of energy between the thermodynamic system and its environment is accompanied neither by a transfer of entropy nor of amounts of constituents.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Unlike an isothermal process, an adiabatic process transfers energy to the surroundings only as work and/or mass flow.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] As a key concept in thermodynamics, the adiabatic process supports the theory that explains the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The opposite term to "adiabatic" is *diabatic*.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Some chemical and physical processes occur too rapidly for energy to enter or leave the system as heat, allowing a convenient "adiabatic approximation".
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] For example, the adiabatic flame temperature uses this approximation to calculate the upper limit of flame temperature by assuming combustion loses no heat to its surroundings.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] In meteorology, adiabatic expansion and cooling of moist air, which can be triggered by winds flowing up and over a mountain for example, can cause the water vapor pressure to exceed the saturation vapor pressure.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Expansion and cooling beyond the saturation vapor pressure is often idealized as a *pseudo-adiabatic process* whereby excess vapor instantly precipitates into water droplets.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The change in temperature of air undergoing pseudo-adiabatic expansion differs from air undergoing adiabatic expansion because latent heat is released by precipitation.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] A process without transfer of thermal energy (heat) to or from a system, so that *Q* = 0, is called adiabatic, and such a system is said to be adiabatically isolated.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The simplifying assumption frequently made is that a process is adiabatic.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] For example, the compression of a gas within a cylinder of an engine is assumed to occur so rapidly that on the time scale of the compression process, little of the system's energy can be transferred out as heat to the surroundings.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Even though the cylinders are not insulated and are quite conductive, that process is idealized to be adiabatic.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The same can be said to be true for the expansion process of such a system.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The assumption of adiabatic isolation is useful and often combined with other such idealizations to calculate a good first approximation of a system's behaviour.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] For example, according to Laplace, when sound travels in a gas, there is no time for heat conduction in the medium, and so the propagation of sound is adiabatic.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] For such an adiabatic process, the modulus of elasticity (Young's modulus) can be expressed as *E* = *γP*, where γ is the ratio of specific heats at constant pressure and at constant volume ( *γ* = ⁠*Cp*/*Cv*⁠) and *P* is the pressure of the gas.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] For a closed system, one may write the first law of thermodynamics as Δ*U* = *Q* − *W*, where Δ*U* denotes the change of the system's internal energy, Q the quantity of energy added to it as heat, and W the work done by the system on its surroundings.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Naturally occurring adiabatic processes are irreversible (entropy is produced).
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The transfer of energy as work into an adiabatically isolated system can be imagined as being of two idealized extreme kinds.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] In one such kind, no entropy is produced within the system (no friction, viscous dissipation, etc.), and the work is only pressure-volume work (denoted by *P* d*V*).
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] In nature, this ideal kind occurs only approximately because it demands an infinitely slow process and no sources of dissipation.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The other extreme kind of work is isochoric work (d*V* = 0), for which energy is added as work solely through friction or viscous dissipation within the system.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] A stirrer that transfers energy to a viscous fluid of an adiabatically isolated system with rigid walls, without phase change, will cause a rise in temperature of the fluid, but that work is not recoverable.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The second law of thermodynamics observes that a natural process, of transfer of energy as work, always consists at least of isochoric work and often both of these extreme kinds of work.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Every natural process, adiabatic or not, is irreversible, with Δ*S* > 0, as friction or viscosity are always present to some extent.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic compression of a gas causes a rise in temperature of the gas.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion against pressure, or a spring, causes a drop in temperature.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] In contrast, free expansion is an isothermal process for an ideal gas.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] This finds practical application in diesel engines which rely on the lack of heat dissipation during the compression stroke to elevate the fuel vapor temperature sufficiently to ignite it.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic compression occurs in the Earth's atmosphere when an air mass descends, for example, in a Katabatic wind, Foehn wind, or Chinook wind flowing downhill over a mountain range.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] When a parcel of air descends, the pressure on the parcel increases.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Because of this increase in pressure, the parcel's volume decreases and its temperature increases as work is done on the parcel of air, thus increasing its internal energy, which manifests itself by a rise in the temperature of that mass of air.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The parcel of air can only slowly dissipate the energy by conduction or radiation (heat), and to a first approximation it can be considered adiabatically isolated and the process an adiabatic process.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs when the pressure on an adiabatically isolated system is decreased, allowing it to expand in size, thus causing it to do work on its surroundings.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] When the pressure applied on a parcel of gas is reduced, the gas in the parcel is allowed to expand; as the volume increases, the temperature falls as its internal energy decreases.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs in the Earth's atmosphere with orographic lifting and lee waves, and this can form pilei or lenticular clouds.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Due in part to adiabatic expansion in mountainous areas, snowfall actually occurs in some parts of the Sahara desert.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion does not have to involve a fluid.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] One technique used to reach very low temperatures (thousandths and even millionths of a degree above absolute zero) is via adiabatic demagnetisation, where the change in magnetic field on a magnetic material is used to provide adiabatic expansion.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Also, the contents of an expanding universe can be described (to first order) as an adiabatically expanding fluid.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Rising magma also undergoes adiabatic expansion before eruption, particularly significant in the case of magmas that rise quickly from great depths such as kimberlites.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] In the Earth's convecting mantle (the asthenosphere) beneath the lithosphere, the mantle temperature is approximately an adiabat.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The slight decrease in temperature with shallowing depth is due to the decrease in pressure the shallower the material is in the Earth.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Such temperature changes can be quantified using the ideal gas law, or the hydrostatic equation for atmospheric processes.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] In practice, no process is truly adiabatic.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Many processes rely on a large difference in time scales of the process of interest and the rate of heat dissipation across a system boundary, and thus are approximated by using an adiabatic assumption.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] There is always some heat loss, as no perfect insulators exist.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Here CP is the specific heat for constant pressure, CV is the specific heat for constant volume, and f is the number of degrees of freedom (3 for a monatomic gas, 5 for a diatomic gas or a gas of linear molecules such as carbon dioxide).
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] For a monatomic ideal gas, *γ* = ⁠5/3⁠, and for a diatomic gas (such as nitrogen and oxygen, the main components of air), *γ* = ⁠7/5⁠.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Note that the above formula is only applicable to classical ideal gases (that is, gases far above absolute zero temperature) and not Bose–Einstein or Fermi gases.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] where T is the absolute or thermodynamic temperature.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The compression stroke in a gasoline engine can be used as an example of adiabatic compression.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] so the adiabatic constant for this example is about 6.31 Pa·m4.2 .
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The gas is now compressed to a 0.1 L (0.0001 m3) volume, which we assume happens quickly enough that no heat enters or leaves the gas through the walls.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] We can solve for the temperature of the compressed gas in the engine cylinder as well, using the ideal gas law, P V = n R T (n is amount of gas in moles and R the gas constant for that gas).
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] That is a final temperature of 753 K, or 479 °C, or 896 °F, well above the ignition point of many fuels.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] A diesel engine operates under even more extreme conditions, with compression ratios of 16:1 or more being typical, in order to provide a very high gas pressure, which ensures immediate ignition of the injected fuel.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] For an adiabatic free expansion of an ideal gas, the gas is contained in an insulated container and then allowed to expand in a vacuum.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Because there is no external pressure for the gas to expand against, the work done by or on the system is zero.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Since this process does not involve any heat transfer or work, the first law of thermodynamics then implies that the net internal energy change of the system is zero.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] For an ideal gas, the temperature remains constant because the internal energy only depends on temperature in that case.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Since at constant temperature, the entropy is proportional to the volume, the entropy increases in this case, therefore this process is irreversible.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The definition of an adiabatic process is that heat transfer to the system is zero, *δQ* = 0.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] where d*U* is the change in the internal energy of the system and *δW* is work done *by* the system.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Any work (*δW*) done must be done at the expense of internal energy U, since no heat δQ is being supplied from the surroundings.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] However, P does not remain constant during an adiabatic process but instead changes along with V.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] It is desired to know how the values of d*P* and d*V* relate to each other as the adiabatic process proceeds.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] where α is the number of degrees of freedom divided by 2, R is the universal gas constant and n is the number of moles in the system (a constant).
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Equation (a4) is often expressed as d*U* = *n CV*d*T* because *CV* = *α R* .
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] An adiabat is a curve of constant entropy in a diagram.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Some properties of adiabats on a *P* – *V* diagram are indicated.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] These properties may be read from the classical behaviour of ideal gases, except in the region where P V becomes small (low temperature), where quantum effects become important.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Each adiabat intersects each isotherm exactly once.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] An adiabat looks similar to an isotherm, except that during an expansion, an adiabat loses more pressure than an isotherm, so it has a steeper inclination (more vertical).
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] If isotherms are concave towards the north-east direction (45° from V axis), then adiabats are concave towards the east north-east (31° from V axisaxis).
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] If adiabats and isotherms are graphed at regular intervals of entropy and temperature, respectively (like altitude on a contour map), then as the eye moves towards the axes (towards the south-west), it sees the density of isotherms stay constant, but it sees the density of adiabats grow.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The exception is very near absolute zero, where the density of adiabats drops sharply and they become rare (see Nernst's theorem).
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The term *adiabatic* (/ˌædiəˈbætɪk/) is an anglicization of the Greek term ἀδιάβατος "impassable" (used by Xenophon of rivers).
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] It is used in the thermodynamic sense by Rankine (1866), and adopted by Maxwell in 1871 (explicitly attributing the term to Rankine).
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The etymological origin corresponds here to an impossibility of transfer of energy as heat and of transfer of matter across the wall.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The Greek word ἀδιάβατος is formed from privative ἀ- ("not") and διαβατός, "passable", in turn deriving from διά ("through"), and βαῖνειν ("to walk, go, come").
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Furthermore, in atmospheric thermodynamics, a diabatic process is one in which heat is exchanged.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] An adiabatic process is the opposite – a process in which no heat is exchanged.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process has been important for thermodynamics since its early days.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] It was important in the work of Joule because it provided a way of nearly directly relating quantities of heat and work.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Energy can enter or leave a thermodynamic system enclosed by walls that prevent mass transfer only as heat or work.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Therefore, a quantity of work in such a system can be related almost directly to an equivalent quantity of heat in a cycle of two limbs.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The first limb is an isochoric adiabatic work process increasing the system's internal energy; the second, an isochoric and workless heat transfer returning the system to its original state.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Accordingly, Rankine measured quantity of heat in units of work, rather than as a calorimetric quantity.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] In 1854, Rankine used a quantity that he called "the thermodynamic function" that later was called entropy, and at that time he wrote also of the "curve of no transmission of heat", which he later called an adiabatic curve.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Besides its two isothermal limbs, Carnot's cycle has two adiabatic limbs.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] For the foundations of thermodynamics, the conceptual importance of this was emphasized by Bryan, by Carathéodory, and by Born.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The reason is that calorimetry presupposes a type of temperature as already defined before the statement of the first law of thermodynamics, such as one based on empirical scales.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Such a presupposition involves making the distinction between empirical temperature and absolute temperature.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Rather, the definition of absolute thermodynamic temperature is best left till the second law is available as a conceptual basis.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] In the eighteenth century, the law of conservation of energy was not yet fully formulated or established, and the nature of heat was debated.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] One approach to these problems was to regard heat, measured by calorimetry, as a primary substance that is conserved in quantity.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] By the middle of the nineteenth century, it was recognized as a form of energy, and the law of conservation of energy was thereby also recognized.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The view that eventually established itself, and is currently regarded as right, is that the law of conservation of energy is a primary axiom, and that heat is to be analyzed as consequential.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] In this light, heat cannot be a component of the total energy of a single body because it is not a state variable but, rather, a variable that describes a transfer between two bodies.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process is important because it is a logical ingredient of this current view.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] This present article is written from the viewpoint of macroscopic thermodynamics, and the word *adiabatic* is used in this article in the traditional way of thermodynamics, introduced by Rankine.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] It is pointed out in the present article that, for example, if a compression of a gas is rapid, then there is little time for heat transfer to occur, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] In this sense, a rapid compression of a gas is sometimes approximately or loosely said to be *adiabatic*, though often far from isentropic, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Some authors, like Pippard, recommend using "adiathermal" to refer to processes where no heat-exchange occurs (such as Joule expansion), and "adiabatic" to reversible quasi-static adiathermal processes (so that rapid compression of a gas is *not* "adiabatic").
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] And Laidler has summarized the complicated etymology of "adiabatic".
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Quantum mechanics and quantum statistical mechanics, however, use the word *adiabatic* in a very different sense, one that can at times seem almost opposite to the classical thermodynamic sense.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] In quantum theory, the word *adiabatic* can mean something perhaps near isentropic, or perhaps near quasi-static, but the usage of the word is very different between the two disciplines.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] On the one hand, in quantum theory, if a perturbative element of compressive work is done almost infinitely slowly (that is to say quasi-statically), it is said to have been done *adiabatically*.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The idea is that the shapes of the eigenfunctions change slowly and continuously, so that no quantum jump is triggered, and the change is virtually reversible.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] While the occupation numbers are unchanged, nevertheless there is change in the energy levels of one-to-one corresponding, pre- and post-compression, eigenstates.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Thus a perturbative element of work has been done without heat transfer and without introduction of random change within the system.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] In that theory, such a rapid change is said not to be *adiabatic*, and the contrary word *diabatic* is applied to it.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Recent research suggests that the power absorbed from the perturbation corresponds to the rate of these non-adiabatic transitions.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] This corresponds to the classical process of energy transfer in the form of heat, but with the relative time scales reversed in the quantum case.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Quantum adiabatic processes occur over relatively long time scales, while classical adiabatic processes occur over relatively short time scales.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] It should also be noted that the concept of 'heat' (in reference to the quantity of thermal energy transferred) breaks down at the quantum level, and the specific form of energy (typically electromagnetic) must be considered instead.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The small or negligible absorption of energy from the perturbation in a quantum adiabatic process provides a good justification for identifying it as the quantum analogue of adiabatic processes in classical thermodynamics, and for the reuse of the term.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] In classical thermodynamics, such a rapid change would still be called adiabatic because the system is adiabatically isolated, and there is no transfer of energy as heat.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The strong irreversibility of the change, due to viscosity or other entropy production, does not impinge on this classical usage.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] Thus for a mass of gas, in macroscopic thermodynamics, words are so used that a compression is sometimes loosely or approximately said to be adiabatic if it is rapid enough to avoid significant heat transfer, even if the system is not adiabatically isolated.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] But in quantum statistical theory, a compression is not called adiabatic if it is rapid, even if the system is adiabatically isolated in the classical thermodynamic sense of the term.
[src:knot-unit/adiabatic-process] The words are used differently in the two disciplines, as stated just above.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Admiralty charts have been produced by UKHO for over 200 years, with the primary aim of saving and protecting lives at sea.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] The core market for these charts includes over 40,000 defence and merchant ships globally.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Today, their products are used by over 90% of ships trading internationally.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] The British admiralty charts are compiled, drawn and issued by the Hydrographic Office.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] This department of the Admiralty was established under Earl Spencer by an order in council in 1795, consisting of the Hydrographer, Alexander Dalrymple, one assistant and a draughtsman.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] The initial remit was to organise the charts and information in the office, and to make it available to His Majesty's ships.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] The Hydrographic Department began printing charts in 1800, with the acquisition of its first printing press.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Initially charts were produced only for use by the Navy, but in 1821, Thomas Hurd, who had succeeded Dalrymple as Hydrographer in 1808, persuaded the Admiralty to allow sales to the public.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] The first catalogue of Admiralty charts was published in 1825, and listed 756 charts.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Plates were engraved, in reverse, with a burin.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] The plate was inked, and the excess ink wiped from the flat surface before printing, so that ink remained only in the engraved lines (intaglio printing).
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] The process allowed very fine detail to be printed, but was slow.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] When corrections or alterations were needed to a chart, the copper was hammered from behind, the raised section scraped and smoothed, and the new information engraved on the smoothed area.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] This allowed plates to continue in use for long periods, in some cases for over a hundred years.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Charts often showed a great deal of detail of features on land as well as sea.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Depths were shown by individual soundings while hills and mountains were shown by hatch marks.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Printing was in black and white, but some charts were hand-coloured, either to emphasise water depth or terrain, or to indicate specific features such as lighthouses.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Experiments were made with the use of lithography from the 1820s, but results were not entirely satisfactory.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Lithography was less expensive, and some charts were printed in this way, but printing from copper plates continued to be the main method into the 20th-Century, and in both cases from flat-bed printing machines.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] The most common chart size was early established as the "Double-elephant", about 39 X 25.5 inches, and this has continued to be the case.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Chart design gradually simplified over the years, with less detail on land, focusing on features visible to the mariner.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Contours were increasingly used for hills instead of hatching.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] All printing of Admiralty charts was carried out in England until the first World War.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] In 1915, the survey ship HMS *Endeavour* was sent to support the Gallipoli campaign, and carried printing equipment so that charts from her surveys could be rapidly made available to the fleet.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] In 1938 trials were made with the rotary offset process, using a zinc plate copied from the copper original.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] These were successful, and by the outbreak of World War II all chart production used this process, which was faster, and reduced wear and tear on the copper original.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] This development was crucial in meeting the increased wartime demand for charts.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] During World War II the distribution of printing facilities was on a much larger scale than previously.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] There was also concern about the safety of the original printing plates in the event of air raids, and high quality baryta paper proofs were made as backups.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] From the late 1940s, developments in printing technology made colour printing possible with sufficient accuracy for chart work.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] The first use of printed (as opposed to hand-drawn) colour was in marking of water depths.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Solid pale blue was used for water to the 3 fathom line, and a ribbon of blue for six fathoms.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Metrication of Admiralty charts began in 1967, and it was decided to synchronise this with the introduction of a new style of chart, with increased use of colour, which continues in use today.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] The most striking change is the use of buff for land.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Green is used for drying (intertidal) areas, and magenta to indicate lights and beacons.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Thus the chart coloration gave a clear indication to users as to whether they were using a chart with depths in fathoms or feet.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] While depths and heights were in metres, the nautical mile continued to be an international standard.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Derived from the length of 1 minute of latitude, it is defined as 1852 metres.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Initially, surveys and explorations continued to be commissioned directly by the Admiralty, for example Flinders' circumnavigation of Australia in 1801–3, and Beaufort's survey of the southern coast of Turkey (then called Karamania) in 1811–1812.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Under Hurd, the Hydrographic Office became more involved in surveying work, and by 1817 there were three vessels specifically assigned to the surveying service, HMS *Protector*, HMS *Shamrock*, and HMS *Congo*.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] This continued, particularly under Francis Beaufort, Hydrographer from 1829 to 1855.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Over the following century the surveying service expanded in both size and reach, becoming a global operation.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Several accounts record this history in detail.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Llewellyn Styles Dawson was a surveyor particularly noted for his work in China (1865-1870) and a naval assistant in the department for five years (1876-1881).
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] During the latter period he commenced work on the two-volume *Memoirs of Hydrography* which described the Royal Navy's surveying activities between 1750 and 1885, and presented biographies of the officers involved in the activities.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] The history was continued to 1917 by Archibald Day, Hydrographer from 1950 to 1955 in his *The Admiralty Hydrographic Service from 1795-1919*, explicitly described as a continuation of Dawson's *Memoirs*.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Thomas Henry Tizard published a chronological list of the officers and vessels conducting British maritime discoveries and surveys until 1900.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] These works are all in the public domain.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Roger Morris, Hydrographer from 1985 to 1990, published *Charts and Surveys in Peace and War 1919-1970*, a further continuation of *Memoirs*.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] A less formal account of British Naval Hydrography in the 19th-Century is given by Steve Ritchie, Hydrographer 1966–1971, in *The Admiralty Chart*.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Tony Rice has produced a listing and description of the vessels involved in surveying and oceanographic work from 1800 to 1950.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] A number of major overseas surveys were completed in the years to 1855, a period dominated by Francis Beaufort, Hydrographer from 1829 to 1855.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Owen carried out his survey of East Africa from the Cape of Good Hope to Cape Guardafui on the Horn of Africa in 1822–1825, an operation that cost the lives of more than half of the crew due to tropical illness.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Thomas Graves was working in the Mediterranean from 1836 to 1850.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Like a number of surveyors before and since, he explored the antiquities and natural history of the numerous places he charted.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] In 1841-7 Edward Belcher was engaged in the Far East, including making the first survey of Hong Kong.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] The longest running survey was that of Bayfield, whose survey of the Canadian coasts, the St.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Lawrence River and the Great Lakes occupied him from 1816 to 1856.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Surveys in home waters were also important.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] What Robinson (1962) described as the "Grand Survey of the British Isles" began with the appointment of George Thomas as Head Maritime surveyor.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Thomas and a series of able surveyors including Michael Slater, Henry Otter, Charles Robinson, William Hewett and Frederick Beechey surveyed the coasts of Britain and Ireland over the next 30 years.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Thomas developed techniques for extending triangulation over the shallow waters of the Thames Estuary and the southern part of the North Sea, allowing the exact positions of treacherous sand banks to be determined for the first time.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] These surveys added large numbers of new charts, as well as improvements to old ones.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] By 1855, when Beaufort retired, the survey of the coasts of the United Kingdom was complete, and there were about 2,000 charts in the catalogue, covering all the oceans of the world.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] An important survey in 1870 was the Suez Canal.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Britain had remained aloof in the early stages of the project, believing it to be impracticable.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] When the canal was nearing completion, the question arose as to its suitability for naval ships.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] George Nares in HMS *Newport* traversed the canal in both directions taking soundings and making measurements, and also surveyed the approaches.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] This led to the canal becoming an established route for the Royal Navy.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] As well as the "grand surveys" much detailed work was needed.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] A particular concern was finding isolated rocks.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] These were easily missed by soundings with lead and line, which did not give any information about the depths between the soundings.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] In 1887, two ships were lost in the southern Red Sea, fortunately without loss of life, after striking an uncharted reef close to a major shipping lane.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Several attempts to find this were made before HMS *Stork* found it (and nearly struck it) in 1888.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] It was named Avocet Rock after the first ship to strike it.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Technical developments over the years improved surveying methods and the accuracy of the charts.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] For depth determination, methods of measuring depth from a moving ship were developed, as well as "sweeping", dragging a horizontal line across an area to detect hazards that might be missed by individual soundings.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Echo sounding was introduced in the 1920s, and Percy Douglas, hydrographer from 1924 to 1932, was a strong advocate of this method.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] As well as increasing productivity, it enabled continuous monitoring along a sounding line, reducing the chance of a hazard being missed.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Isolated rocks between sounding lines could still be missed, and it was not until the development of sideways-looking sonar in the 1960s and 70s that this risk could be eliminated.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Most navigation today uses GPS chart plotters with electronic charts.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Paper charts continue to be issued, and are valuable for passage planning and course plotting.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] The scale of the charts can vary according to purpose; large-scale charts often cover approaches to harbours, such as Port Approach Guides, medium-scale charts often cover frequently used coastal areas, and small-scale charts are regularly used for navigation in more open areas.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] A series of small craft charts are also available at suitable scales.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Navigation charts at a scale of 1:50,000 or smaller (1:100,000 is a smaller scale than 1:50,000) use the Mercator projection, and have since at least the 1930s.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] The Mercator projection has the property of maintaining angles correctly, so that a line on the earth's surface that crosses all the meridians at the same angle (a rhumb line) will be represented on the chart by a straight line at the same angle.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Thus if a straight line is drawn on the chart from A to B, and the angle determined, the ship may sail at a constant bearing at that angle to reach B from A.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Allowances for magnetic variation and magnetic deviation must also be made.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] However, a rhumb line is not in general the shortest distance between two points, which is a great circle.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] (The equator and lines of longitude are both great circles and rhumb lines.) When navigating over longer distances the difference becomes important, and charts using the gnomonic projection, on which all great circles are shown as straight lines, are used for course planning.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] In the past, the gnomonic projection was widely used for navigation charts, and also for polar charts.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Since the late 1970s, all charts at a scale of 1:50,000 or larger have used the transverse Mercator projection, which is the projection used for the Ordnance Survey National Grid.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Topography on Admiralty charts of the UK is generally based on Ordnance Survey mapping.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] For the small areas depicted on such maps, the differences between projections are of no practical importance.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Admiralty charts are issued by the UKHO for a variety of users; Standard Nautical Charts (SNCs) are issued to mariners subject to the Safety of Life at Sea (SOLAS) convention, while chart folios, at a convenient A2 size, are produced for leisure users.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Alongside its paper charts, UKHO produces an expanding range of digital products to fulfil the impending compulsory carriage requirements of ECDIS/ENCs, as issued by the International Maritime Organization (IMO).
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] The digital range comprises Electronic Navigational Charts (ENCs) for use with an Electronic Chart Display and Information System (ECDIS), which can be displayed and interrogated through Admiralty Vector Chart Service (AVCS).
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] The range also includes Admiralty Raster Chart Service (ARCS), which allows paper nautical charts to be viewed in raster form on an ECDIS.
[src:knot-unit/admiralty-chart] Due to the changing nature of the seabed and other charted features, chart information must be up-to-date to maintain accuracy and general safety.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] In aviation, **airspeed** is the speed of an aircraft relative to the air it is flying through (which itself is usually moving relative to the ground due to wind).
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] In contrast, the ground speed is the speed of an aircraft with respect to the surface of the Earth (whether over land or presumed-stationary water).
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] It is difficult to measure the exact airspeed of the aircraft (true airspeed), but other measures of airspeed, such as indicated airspeed and Mach number give useful information about the capabilities and limitations of airplane performance.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] The measurement and indication of airspeed is ordinarily accomplished on board an aircraft by an airspeed indicator (ASI) connected to a pitot-static system.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] The pitot-static system comprises one or more pitot probes (or tubes) facing the on-coming air flow to measure pitot pressure (also called stagnation, total or ram pressure) and one or more static ports to measure the static pressure in the air flow.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] These two pressures are compared by the ASI to give an IAS reading.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Airspeed indicators are designed to give true airspeed at sea level pressure and standard temperature.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] As the aircraft climbs into less dense air, its true airspeed is greater than the airspeed indicated on the ASI.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Calibrated airspeed is typically within a few knots of indicated airspeed, while equivalent airspeed decreases slightly from CAS as aircraft altitude increases or at high speeds.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Airspeed is commonly given in knots (kn).
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Since 2010, the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) recommends using kilometers per hour (km/h) for airspeed (and meters per second for wind speed on runways), but allows using the de facto standard of knots, and has no set date on when to stop.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Depending on the country of manufacture or which era in aviation history, airspeed indicators on aircraft instrument panels have been configured to read in knots, kilometers per hour, miles per hour.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] In high altitude flight, the Mach number is sometimes used for reporting airspeed.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Indicated airspeed (IAS) is the airspeed indicator reading (ASIR) uncorrected for instrument, position, and other errors.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] From current EASA definitions: Indicated airspeed means the speed of an aircraft as shown on its pitot static airspeed indicator calibrated to reflect standard atmosphere adiabatic compressible flow at sea level uncorrected for airspeed system errors.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] An airspeed indicator is a differential pressure gauge with the pressure reading expressed in units of speed, rather than pressure.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] The airspeed is derived from the difference between the ram air pressure from the pitot tube, or stagnation pressure, and the static pressure.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] The pitot tube is mounted facing forward; the static pressure is frequently detected at static ports on one or both sides of the aircraft.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Sometimes both pressure sources are combined in a single probe, a pitot-static tube.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] The static pressure measurement is subject to error due to inability to place the static ports at positions where the pressure is true static pressure at all airspeeds and attitudes.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] The correction for this error is the position error correction (PEC) and varies for different aircraft and airspeeds.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Further errors of 10% or more are common if the airplane is flown in "uncoordinated" flight.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Indicated airspeed is a better measure of power required and lift available than true airspeed.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Therefore, IAS is used for controlling the aircraft during taxiing, takeoff, climb, descent, approach or landing.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Target speeds for best rate of climb, best range, and best endurance are given in terms of indicated speed.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] The airspeed structural limit, beyond which the forces on panels may become too high or wing flutter may occur, is often given in terms of IAS.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Calibrated airspeed (CAS) is indicated airspeed corrected for instrument errors, position error (due to incorrect pressure at the static port) and installation errors.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] This expression is based on the form of Bernoulli's equation applicable to isentropic compressible flow.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] CAS is the same as true air speed at sea level standard conditions, but becomes smaller relative to true airspeed as we climb into lower pressure and cooler air.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Nevertheless, it remains a good measure of the forces acting on the airplane, meaning stall speeds can be called out on the airspeed indicator.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] The values for $p_{0}$ and $a_{0}$ are consistent with the ISA i.e. the conditions under which airspeed indicators are calibrated.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] The **true airspeed** (**TAS**; also **KTAS**, for *knots true airspeed*) of an aircraft is the speed of the aircraft relative to the air in which it is flying.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] The true airspeed and heading of an aircraft constitute its velocity relative to the atmosphere.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] The true airspeed is important information for accurate navigation of an aircraft.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] To maintain a desired ground track whilst flying in a moving airmass, the pilot of an aircraft must use knowledge of wind speed, wind direction, and true air speed to determine the required heading.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] TAS is the appropriate speed to use when calculating the range of an airplane.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] It is the speed normally listed on the flight plan, also used in flight planning, before considering the effects of wind.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Some airspeed indicators include a TAS scale, which is set by entering outside air temperature and pressure altitude.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Alternatively, TAS can be calculated using an E6B flight calculator or equivalent, given inputs of CAS, outside air temperature (OAT) and pressure altitude.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Equivalent airspeed (EAS) is defined as the airspeed at sea level in the International Standard Atmosphere at which the (incompressible) dynamic pressure is the same as the dynamic pressure at the true airspeed (TAS) and altitude at which the aircraft is flying.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] EAS is a measure of airspeed that is a function of incompressible dynamic pressure.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Structural analysis is often in terms of incompressible dynamic pressure, so equivalent airspeed is a useful speed for structural testing.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] The significance of equivalent airspeed is that, at Mach numbers below the onset of wave drag, all of the aerodynamic forces and moments on an aircraft are proportional to the square of the equivalent airspeed.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Thus, the handling and 'feel' of an aircraft, and the aerodynamic loads upon it, at a given equivalent airspeed, are very nearly constant and equal to those at standard sea level irrespective of the actual flight conditions.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] At standard sea level pressure, CAS and EAS are equal.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Up to about 200 knots CAS and 10,000 ft (3,000 m) the difference is negligible, but at higher speeds and altitudes CAS diverges from EAS due to compressibility.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Both the Mach number and the speed of sound can be computed using measurements of impact pressure, static pressure and outside air temperature.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] For aircraft that fly close to, but below the speed of sound (i.e. most civil jets) the compressibility speed limit is given in terms of Mach number.
[src:knot-unit/air-speed] Beyond this speed, Mach buffet or stall or tuck may occur.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] The **airspeed indicator** (**ASI**) or **airspeed gauge** is a flight instrument indicating the airspeed of an aircraft in kilometres per hour (km/h), knots (kn or kt), miles per hour (MPH) and/or metres per second (m/s).
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] The recommendation by ICAO is to use km/h, however knots (kt) is currently the most used unit.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] The ASI measures the pressure differential between static pressure from the static port, and total pressure from the pitot tube.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] This difference in pressure is registered with the ASI pointer on the face of the instrument.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] The ASI has standard colour-coded markings to indicate safe operation within the limitations of the aircraft.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] At a glance, the pilot can determine a recommended speed (V speeds) or if speed adjustments are needed.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] Single and multi-engine aircraft have common markings.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] For instance, the green arc indicates the normal operating range of the aircraft, from *V*S1 to *V*NO.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] The white arc indicates the flap operating range, *V*SO to *V*FE, used for approaches and landings.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] The yellow arc cautions that flight should be conducted in this range only in smooth air, while the red line (*V*NE) at the top of the yellow arc indicates damage or structural failure may result at higher speeds.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] The ASI in multi-engine aircraft includes two additional radial markings, one red and one blue, associated with potential engine failure.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] The radial red line near the bottom of green arc indicates *V*mc, the minimum indicated airspeed at which the aircraft can be controlled with the critical engine inoperative.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] The radial blue line indicates *V*YSE, the speed for best rate of climb with the critical engine inoperative.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] The ASI is the only flight instrument that uses both the static system and the pitot system.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] Static pressure enters the ASI case, while total pressure flexes the diaphragm, which is connected to the ASI pointer via mechanical linkage.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] The pressures are equal when the aircraft is stationary on the ground, and hence shows a reading of zero.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] When the aircraft is moving forward, air entering the pitot tube is at a greater pressure than the static line, which flexes the diaphragm, moving the pointer.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] The ASI is checked before takeoff for a zero reading, and during takeoff that it is increasing appropriately.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] The pitot tube may become blocked, because of insects, dirt or failure to remove the pitot cover.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] A blockage will prevent ram air from entering the system.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] If the pitot opening is blocked, but the drain hole is open, the system pressure will drop to ambient pressure, and the ASI pointer will drop to a zero reading.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] If both the opening and drain holes are blocked, the ASI will not indicate any change in airspeed.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] However, the ASI pointer will show altitude changes, as the associated static pressure changes.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] If both the pitot tube and the static system are blocked, the ASI pointer will read zero.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] If the static ports are blocked but the pitot tube remains open, the ASI will operate, but inaccurately.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] The pilot sets the pressure altitude and air temperature in the top window using the knob.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] Based on that, the white background scale in the lower left window moves to give true airspeed.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] There are four types of airspeed that can be remembered with the acronym ICE-T.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] Indicated airspeed (**IAS**), is read directly off the ASI.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] It has no correction for air density variations, installation or instrument errors.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] Calibrated airspeed (**CAS**) is corrected for installation and instrument errors.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] Equivalent airspeed (**EAS**) is calibrated airspeed (CAS) corrected for the compressibility of air at a non-trivial Mach number.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] True airspeed (**TAS**) is CAS corrected for altitude and nonstandard temperature.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] TAS increases as altitude increases, as air density decreases.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] TAS may be determined via a flight computer, such as the E6B.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] Alternatively, a rule of thumb is to add 2 percent to the CAS for every 1,000 ft (300 m) of altitude gained.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] Jet aircraft do not have *VNO* and *VNE* like piston-engined aircraft, but instead have a maximum operating speed expressed in knots, *VMO* and Mach number, *MMO*.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] Thus, a pilot of a jet aeroplane needs both an airspeed indicator and a Machmeter, with appropriate red lines.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] An ASI will include a red-and-white striped pointer, or "barber's pole", that automatically moves to indicate the applicable speed limit at any given time.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] An aeroplane can stall at any speed, so monitoring the ASI alone will not prevent a stall.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] The critical angle of attack (AOA) determines when an aircraft will stall.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] For a particular configuration, it is a constant independent of weight, bank angle, temperature, density altitude, and the center of gravity of an aircraft.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] An AOA indicator provides stall situational awareness as a means for monitoring the onset of the critical AOA.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] The AOA indicator will show the current AOA and its proximity to the critical AOA.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] Similarly, the Lift Reserve Indicator (LRI) provides a measure of the amount of lift being generated.
[src:knot-unit/airspeed-indicator] It uses a pressure differential system to provide the pilot with a visual representation of reserve lift available.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Aviation began in the 18th century with the development of the hot air balloon, an apparatus capable of atmospheric displacement through buoyancy.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Clément Ader built the "Ader Éole" in France and made an uncontrolled, powered hop in 1890.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] This was the first powered aircraft, although it did not achieve controlled flight.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Some of the most significant advancements in aviation technology came with the controlled gliding flying of Otto Lilienthal in 1896.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] A major leap followed with the construction of the *Wright Flyer*, the first powered airplane by the Wright brothers in the early 1900s.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Since that time, aviation has been technologically revolutionized by the introduction of the jet engine which enabled aviation to become a major form of transport throughout the world.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] In 2024, there were 9.5 billion passengers worldwide according to the ICAO.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] As of 2018, estimates suggest that 11% of the world's population traveled by air, with up to 4% taking international flights.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The word *aviation* was coined by the French writer and former naval officer Gabriel de La Landelle in 1863.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] He originally derived the term from the verb *avier* (an unsuccessful neologism for "to fly"), itself derived from the Latin word *avis* ("bird") and the suffix *-ation*.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] There are early legends of human flight such as the stories of Icarus in Greek myth, Jamshid and Shah Kay Kāvus in Persian myth, and the flying automaton of Archytas of Tarentum (428–347 BC).
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The modern age of aviation began with the first untethered human lighter-than-air flight on November 21, 1783, of a hot air balloon designed by the Montgolfier brothers.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The usefulness of balloons was limited because they could only travel downwind.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The first steerable dirigible, balloon was flown by Jean-Pierre Blanchard in 1784.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] It was human-powered and, Blanchard completed a successful crossing of the English Channel in one in 1785.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Rigid airships became the first aircraft to transport passengers and cargo over great distances.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The best-known aircraft of this type were manufactured by the German Zeppelin company.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The most successful Zeppelin was the *Graf Zeppelin*.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] It flew over one million miles, including an around-the-world flight in August 1929.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] However, the dominance of the Zeppelins over the airplanes of that period, which had a range of only a few hundred miles, was diminishing as airplane design advanced.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The era of passenger airships ended on May 6, 1937 when the *Hindenburg* caught fire, killing 36 people.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The cause of the accident has been debated ever since.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Several investigations concluded a spark ignited leaking flammable hydrogen lifting gas.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] An internal investigation by the manufacturer found that the coating used in the material covering the frame was highly flammable and allowed static electricity to build up in the airship.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Changes to the coating formulation reduced the risk of subsequent accidents.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Although there have been periodic initiatives to revive their use, airships have seen only niche application since that time.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] There had been previous airship accidents that were more fatal, for instance, a British R38 on 23 August 1921, but the *Hindenburg* was the first to be captured on newsreel.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] In 1799, Sir George Cayley set forth the concept of the modern airplane as a fixed-wing flying machine with separate systems for lift, propulsion and control.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Otto Lilienthal was the first person to make well-documented, repeated, successful flights with gliders, therefore making the idea of "heavier than air" a reality.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Newspapers and magazines published photographs of Lilienthal gliding, favorably influencing public and scientific opinion about the possibility of flying machines becoming practical.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Lilienthal's work led him to develop the concept of the modern wing.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] His flight attempts in Berlin in 1891 are seen as the beginning of human flight and the Lilienthal *Normalsegelapparat* is considered to be the first airplane in series production, making the *Maschinenfabrik Otto Lilienthal* in Berlin the first air plane production company in the world.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Lilienthal is often referred to as either the "father of aviation" or "father of flight".
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The late 19th and early 20th centuries saw dirigible developments, such as Henri Giffard's included machine-powered propulsion Giffard dirigible in 1852, David Schwarz' rigid frame dirigible in 1896 and Alberto Santos-Dumont's improvements to speed and maneuverability in 1901.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] There are many competing claims for the earliest powered, heavier-than-air flight.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The first recorded powered flight was carried out by Clément Ader on October 9, 1890, in his bat-winged, fully self-propelled fixed-wing aircraft, the Ader Éole.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] It was reportedly the first manned, powered, heavier-than-air flight of a significant distance of 50 meters (160 ft), but insignificant altitude from level ground.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Seven years later, on October 14, 1897, Ader's Avion III was tested without success in front of two officials from the French War ministry.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The report on the trials was not publicized until 1910, as they had been a military secret.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] In November 1906, Ader said that he made a successful flight on October 14, 1897 and achieved an uninterrupted flight of around 300 meters (980 feet).
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Although widely believed at the time, these claims were later discredited.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The Wright brothers made the first successful powered, controlled and sustained airplane flight on December 17, 1903, a feat made possible by their invention of three-axis control and in-house development of an engine with a sufficient power-to-weight ratio.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] A decade later, at the start of World War I, heavier-than-air powered aircraft had become practical for reconnaissance, artillery spotting and attacks against ground positions.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Aircraft began to transport people and cargo as designs grew larger and more reliable.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The Wright brothers took aloft the first passenger, Charles Furnas, one of their mechanics, on May 14, 1908.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] During the 1920s and 1930s great progress was made in the field of aviation, including the first transatlantic flight of Alcock and Brown in 1919, Charles Lindbergh's solo transatlantic flight in 1927 and Charles Kingsford Smith's transpacific flight the following year.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] One of the most successful designs of this period was the Douglas DC-3, which became the first airliner to be profitable carrying passengers exclusively, starting the modern era of passenger airline service.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] By the beginning of World War II, many towns and cities had built airports, and there were numerous qualified pilots available.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] During World War II one of the first jet engines was developed by Hans von Ohain and accomplished the world's first jet-powered flight in 1939.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The war brought many innovations to aviation, including the first jet aircraft and the first liquid-fueled rockets.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] After World War II, especially in North America, there was a boom in general aviation, both private and commercial, as thousands of pilots were released from military service and many inexpensive war-surplus transport and training aircraft became available.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Manufacturers such as Cessna, Piper, and Beechcraft expanded production to provide light aircraft for the new middle-class market.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] By the 1950s, the development of civil jets grew, beginning with the de Havilland Comet, though the first widely used passenger jet was the Boeing 707, because it was much more economical than other aircraft at that time.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] At the same time, turboprop propulsion started to appear for smaller commuter planes, making it possible to serve small-volume routes in a much wider range of weather conditions.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Since the 1960s composite material airframes and quieter, more efficient engines have become available, and Concorde provided supersonic passenger service for more than two decades.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] However, the most important lasting innovations have taken place in instrumentation and control.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The arrival of solid-state electronics, the Global Positioning System, satellite communications, and increasingly small and powerful computers and LED displays, have dramatically changed the cockpits of airliners and, increasingly, of smaller aircraft as well.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Pilots can navigate much more accurately and view terrain, obstructions, and other nearby aircraft on a map or through synthetic vision, even at night or in low visibility.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] On June 21, 2004, SpaceShipOne became the first privately funded aircraft to make a spaceflight, opening the possibility of an aviation market capable of leaving the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Meanwhile, the need to decarbonize the aviation industry to face the climate crisis has increased research into aircraft powered by alternative fuels, such as ethanol, electricity, hydrogen, and solar energy, with flying prototypes becoming more common.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Civil aviation includes all non-military flying, both general aviation and scheduled air transport.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Boeing, Airbus, Ilyushin and Tupolev concentrate on wide-body and narrow-body jet airliners, while Bombardier, Embraer and Sukhoi concentrate on regional airliners.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Large networks of specialized parts suppliers from around the world support these manufacturers, who sometimes provide only the initial design and final assembly in their own plants.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The Chinese ACAC consortium has also entered the civil transport market with its Comac ARJ21 regional jet in june, 2016.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Until the 1970s, most major airlines were flag carriers, sponsored by their governments and heavily protected from competition.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Since then, open skies agreements have resulted in increased competition and choice for consumers, coupled with falling prices for airlines.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The combination of high fuel prices, low fares, high salaries, as well as crises such as the September 11 attacks and the SARS pandemic have driven many older airlines to government-bailouts, bankruptcy or mergers.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] At the same time, low-cost carriers such as Ryanair, Southwest and WestJet have flourished.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Each country regulates aviation differently, but general aviation usually falls under different regulations depending on whether it is private or commercial and on the type of equipment involved.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Many small aircraft manufacturers serve the general aviation market, with a focus on private aviation and flight training.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The most important recent developments for small aircraft, which form the bulk of the GA fleet, have been the introduction of advanced avionics (including GPS) that were formerly found only in large airliners, and the introduction of composite materials to make small aircraft lighter and faster.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Ultralight and homebuilt aircraft have also become increasingly popular for recreational use, since in most countries that allow private aviation, they are much less expensive and less heavily regulated than certified aircraft.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Simple balloons were used as surveillance aircraft as early as the 18th century.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Over the years, military aircraft have been built to meet ever increasing capability requirements.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Manufacturers of military aircraft compete for contracts to supply their government's arsenal.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Aircraft are selected based on factors like cost, performance and the speed of production.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Aviation safety means the state of an aviation system or organization in which risks associated with aviation activities, related to, or in direct support of the operation of aircraft, are reduced and controlled to an acceptable level.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] It encompasses the theory, practice, investigation, and categorization of flight failures, and the prevention of such failures through regulation, education, and training.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] It can also be applied in the context of campaigns that inform the public as to the safety of air travel.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] A maintenance, repair, and overhaul organization (MRO) is a firm that ensures airworthiness or air transport.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] According to a 2024 article, "maintenance (M) involves inspecting, cleaning, oiling, and changing aircraft parts after a certain number of flight hours.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Repair (R) is restoring the original function of parts and components.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] MRO firms are responsible for this process, thoroughly checking and documenting all components' repairs while tracking mechanical, propulsion, and electronic parts.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Aviation regulators oversee maintenance practices in the country of aircraft registration, manufacture, or current location.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] All aircraft maintenance activities must adhere to international regulations that mandate standards.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] An accident in which the damage to the aircraft is such that it must be written off, or in which the plane is destroyed, is called a *hull loss accident*.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The first fatal aviation accident occurred in a Wright Model A aircraft at Fort Myer (now part of Joint Base Myer–Henderson Hall) in Virginia, on September 17, 1908, resulting in injury to the pilot, Orville Wright, and death of the passenger, Signal Corps Lieutenant Thomas Selfridge.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The worst aviation accident in history was the Tenerife airport disaster on March 27, 1977, when 583 people died when two Boeing 747 jumbo jets, operated by Pan Am and KLM collided on a runway in Los Rodeos airport, now known as Tenerife North.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] An *aviation incident* is defined as an occurrence, other than an accident, associated with the operation of an aircraft that affects or could affect the safety of operations.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Air traffic control (ATC) involves communication with aircraft to help maintain separation – that is, they ensure that aircraft are sufficiently far enough apart horizontally or vertically for no risk of collision.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Controllers may co-ordinate position reports provided by pilots, or in high traffic areas they may use radar to see aircraft positions.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Becoming an air traffic controller in the United States typically requires an associate or bachelor's degree from the Air Traffic Collegiate Training Initiative.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The FAA also requires extensive training, along with medical examinations and background checks.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Some controllers are required to work weekend, night, and holiday shifts.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] ATC is especially important for aircraft flying under instrument flight rules (IFR) when they may be in weather conditions that do not allow the pilots to see other aircraft.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] However, in very high-traffic areas, especially near major airports, aircraft flying under visual flight rules (VFR) are also required to follow instructions from ATC.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] In addition to separation from other aircraft, ATC may provide weather advisories, terrain separation, navigation assistance, and other services to pilots, depending on their workload.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Like all activities involving combustion, operating powered aircraft, from airliners to hot air balloons, releases soot and other pollutants into the atmosphere.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Greenhouse gases such as carbon dioxide (CO2) are also produced.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Another environmental impact of aviation is noise pollution, mainly caused by aircraft taking off and landing.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Sonic booms were a problem with supersonic aircraft such as the Concorde.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Air transportation is a mode of travel and commerce, involving the movement of people, goods, and animals through the atmosphere using aircraft such as airplanes and helicopters.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] It is a major mode for the overall transportation system, because of its speed and the ability to cover long distances quickly, connecting remote regions and major economic hubs.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] It plays a significant role in global trade and passenger mobility, influencing economic development and international relations.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] However, its share of CO2 emissions is significant, accounting for 2% of global CO2 emissions in 2023, having grown faster between 2000 and 2019 than rail, road or shipping.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Even under the High Ambition scenario, where total emissions are reduced significantly, aviation emissions will still be a major concern.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The International Air Transport Association (IATA) has highlighted the need for ambitious policies in order to achieve significant reductions in aviation emissions, projecting that CO2 emissions from aviation could be lowered by up to 50% by 2050 with the right measures in place.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) also emphasizes the potential of accelerating the transition to sustainable aviation fuels (SAFs) and implementing efficiency technologies for both commercial and cargo aircraft to achieve significant emission reductions.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] These commitments reflect a concerted effort by global organizations to address the climate impact of the aviation sector.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Two significant megatrends are observed in terms of air transport innovation, sustainability and digitalization.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] A report published by WIPO in 2025 showed a steady increase of patents publication in air transportation, the majority of which being related to communication and security, followed by sustainable propulsion.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Sustainable Propulsion technologies are being developed to reduce emissions and improve environmental sustainability.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Efficient aircraft turbines are used to improve fuel efficiency, reduce emissions and lower noise levels.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Aviation biofuels aim for a reduction in CO2 emissions compared to traditional jet fuel.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Battery-based electric and/or hybrid aircraft are being developed for short-haul and regional flights.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Hydrogen-powered aircraft are intended for long-haul flights and heavy-duty applications.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Automation and Circularity technologies are promoting efficient material use, smart production and robotics, and enhanced recycling practices.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Communication and Security technologies are impacting air transportation by improving operational efficiency, safety and customer experience.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] They include navigation technologies such as advanced air traffic management (ATM) systems, device-to-device technology, cloud computing, low-latency internet, and cybersecurity.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Analysis by McKinsey & Company has stated that the rise in digital technologies has made aviation systems more vulnerable to cyberattacks, emphasizing the need for robust cybersecurity measures.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The air transportation sector is undergoing a surge in patenting activity, with annual Air transport-related patent families increasing from under 1,100 in 2000 to over 12,800 in 2023 – a growth of 11%.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] China, the South Korea, and Japan stand out for their high patent volumes and significant growth rates, although they exhibit a relatively low Relative Specialization Index, reflecting a broad approach to innovation at the country-level across various sectors.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] In contrast, France, the United States and Canada demonstrate a high degree of specialization in Air transportation technologies reflecting a concentrated focus on advancing specific innovations in aviation.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Leading aviation companies such as RTX, General Electric, Safran, Boeing, Rolls-Royce Holdings, and Honeywell International dominate the patent filings.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The Aero Engine Corporation of China leads in recent growth with a compound annual growth rate of 81.1%.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Generally, Chinese patent owners exhibit strong recent growth in air transport patent, in contrast to the other top patentees.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] Mitsubishi Electric in Japan is the only non-Chinese entity among the fastest-growing patent owners.
[src:knot-unit/aviation] The diverse landscape underscores the dynamic interplay of high-volume patenting and strategic specialization across different regions, driven by both established aviation multinationals and emerging players.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] The **knot** (/nɒt/) is a unit of speed equal to one nautical mile per hour, exactly 1.852 km/h (approximately 1.151 mph or 0.514 m/s).
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] The ISO standard symbol for the knot is **kn**.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] The same symbol is preferred by the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE), while **kt** is also common, especially in aviation, where it is the form recommended by the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO).
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] The knot is used in meteorology, and in maritime and air navigation.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] A vessel travelling at 1 knot along a meridian travels approximately one minute of geographic latitude in one hour.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] The length of the internationally agreed nautical mile is 1852 m.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] The US adopted the international definition in 1954, having previously used the US nautical mile (1853.248 m).
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] The UK adopted the international nautical mile definition in 1970, having previously used the UK Admiralty nautical mile (6080 ft or 1853.184 m).
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] The speeds of vehicles relative to the fluids in which they travel (boat speeds and air speeds) can be measured in knots.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] For consistency, the speeds of navigational fluids (ocean currents, tidal streams, river currents, and wind speeds) are also measured in knots.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] Thus, speed over the ground (SOG; ground speed (GS) in aircraft) and rate of progress towards a distant point ("velocity made good", VMG) can also be given in knots.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] Since 1979, the International Civil Aviation Organization lists the knot as permitted for temporary use in aviation, but no end date to the temporary period has been agreed as of 2024.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] Until the mid-19th century, vessel speed at sea was measured using a chip log.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] This consisted of a wooden panel, attached by line to a reel, and weighted on one edge to float perpendicularly to the water surface and thus present substantial resistance to the water moving around it.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] The chip log was cast over the stern of the moving vessel and the line allowed to pay out.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] Knots tied at a distance of 47 feet 3 inches (14.4018 m) from each other, passed through a sailor's fingers, while another sailor used a 30-second sand-glass (28-second sand-glass is the currently accepted timing) to time the operation.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] The knot count would be reported and used in the sailing master's dead reckoning and navigation.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] This method gives a value for the knot of 20+1⁄4 inches per second or 1.85166 kilometres per hour.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] The difference from the modern definition is less than 0.02%.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] Although the unit *knot* does not fit within the SI system, its retention for nautical and aviation use is important because the length of a nautical mile, upon which the knot is based, is closely related to the longitude/latitude geographic coordinate system.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] As a result, nautical miles and knots are convenient units to use when navigating an aircraft or ship.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] On a standard nautical chart using Mercator projection, the horizontal (East–West) scale varies with latitude.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] On a chart of the North Atlantic, the scale varies by a factor of two from Florida to Greenland.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] A single graphic scale, of the sort on many maps, would therefore be useless on such a chart.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] Since the length of a nautical mile, for practical purposes, is equivalent to about a minute of latitude, a distance in nautical miles on a chart can easily be measured by using dividers and the latitude scales on the sides of the chart.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] Recent British Admiralty charts have a latitude scale down the middle to make this even easier.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] Speed is sometimes incorrectly expressed as "knots per hour", which would mean "nautical miles per hour per hour" and thus would refer to acceleration.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] Prior to 1969, airworthiness standards for civil aircraft in the United States Federal Aviation Regulations specified that distances were to be in statute miles, and speeds in miles per hour.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] In 1969, these standards were progressively amended to specify that distances were to be in nautical miles, and speeds in knots.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] The indicated airspeed is close to the true airspeed only at sea level in standard conditions and at low speeds.
[src:knot-unit/knot-unit] At 11000 m (36000 ft), an indicated airspeed of 300 kn may correspond to a true airspeed of 500 kn in standard conditions.
